Certainly! Below is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word. Before running the program, make sure you have a text file to read from and that you know the word you want to count.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

int main() {
    std::string filename;
    std::string wordToFind;
    std::string word;
    int wordCount = 0;

    // Ask the user for the file name
    std::cout << "Enter the file name: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, filename);

    // Ask the user for the word to count
    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, wordToFind);

    // Open the file
    std::ifstream file(filename);

    // Check if the file is open
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Could not open the file - '" << filename << "'" << std::endl;
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    // Read the file line by line
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        // Convert the line into a stringstream for word-by-word processing
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        while (iss >> word) {
            // Increment count if the current word matches the word to find
            if (word == wordToFind) {
                wordCount++;
            }
        }
    }

    // Close the file
    file.close();

    // Output the result
    std::cout << "The word '" << wordToFind << "' occurred " << wordCount << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To compile and run this program, follow these steps:

1. Save the code to a file named `word_count.cpp`.
2. Open a terminal or command prompt.
3. Navigate to the directory where you saved `word_count.cpp`.
4. Compile the program using a C++ compiler, such as g++, with the command:
   ```
   g++ -o word_count word_count.cpp
   ```
5. Run the compiled program:
   ```
   ./word_count
   ```
   (On Windows, you would run `word_count.exe`)

The program will prompt you to enter the name of the text file and the word you want to count. Make sure the text file is in the same directory as the program or provide the full path to the file.

Please note that this program does a simple string comparison and does not handle cases like punctuation attached to words, different cases (uppercase vs lowercase), or word variations (singular vs plural). To handle such cases, you would need to implement additional text processing.
